<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="481" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[168,776,1223,1757]" pageId="2" pageNumber="481">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[206,316,1563,1587]" pageId="2" pageNumber="481">Remarks.</emphasis>
Although this species is similar to 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="481">B. nanus</emphasis>
, the specimens we have examined are much larger (
<quantity box="[175,301,1630,1655]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8275" pageId="2" pageNumber="481" unit="mm" value="18.275">18.275 mm</quantity>
), with less prominent eyes and shorter anten- niferous tubercles. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Carpintero DJ" box="[541,739,1664,1688]" journalOrPublisher="Acta Scientifica" pageId="2" pageNumber="481" pagination="1 - 33" part="14" refId="ref28956" refString="Carpintero DJ (1980) Nuevos Ectrichodiinae americanos (Insecta - Hemiptera - Reduviidae). Acta Scientifica 14: 1 - 33." title="Nuevos Ectrichodiinae americanos (Insecta - Hemiptera - Reduviidae)" type="journal article" year="1980">Carpintero (1980)</bibRefCitation>
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="481">B. nanus</emphasis>
is a much smaller species (
<quantity box="[528,641,1698,1722]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.512" pageId="2" pageNumber="481" unit="mm" value="15.12">15.12 mm</quantity>
), with much more protruding eyes and longer antenniferous tubercles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
